<br>
Total cards: 40  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">If I don&#39;t know my opponent I grab a Chaos Jile as my starting creature as it makes a great first attacker.  Lots of small creature I of course grab Wudge. Starting spell I grab Entomb.   <br>
<br>
The deck runs a small number of creatures (only 15) but the drawing power of &#39;secrets of the book&#39; and the Dark Twins&#39; huge energize rate makes them able to not care about the cost.  The Jewels are there to help get the cards you really need and to screw up hand denial decks. <br>
<br>
Entombing Thunderquake keeps it out of the hands of your opponent and gives you access to some easy magi kills.  This is done by combining the high energize rate of the Dark Twins and the discard ability of Thunderquake and Maelstrom.  <br>
<br>
Vaporize is to keep any pesky relics out of play.  Take one or two out if know your opponent doesn&#39;t use many relics that stay in play and replace them with extra creatures. <br>
<br>
Shadow Bones make for great boosters on the Chaos Jiles to take down big creatures.  Otherwise they are for making sure your Goraths have enough energy to stay alive and stealing creatures. <br>
 <br>
Of course Harror is last as a Cataclysm/Dark Ayebaw finisher should you need her.   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000"> </Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">DeckTech <BR> For the Players, By the Players  <BR>www.decktech.net </FONT></TD></TR></table> 
